Lanthimos is obviously one of my favorites of all time, and I’ve been so eager to watch his debut feature. This one feels strangely different than the rest of his filmography, though there’re hints of his signature throughout. The consistent handheld camera, for instance, is a surprise coming from someone I’ve only known as extremely precise and smooth. But then there’re tableaus, where his characters feel almost ominously bizarre—feels more like the Lanthimos I’m familiar with. My biggest take-away: this…

Movie: Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid

Review: I watched this nearly a month ago as I write, and this movie is still lodged in my memories. Soo damn good!

She never worked on a studio’s terms, she created her own rules. She didn’t make decisions based on what an audience or what critics might say, she simply created from a place of pure empathy and inspiration. If more filmmakers could be as fearless to experiment as she was, cinema would be pushing far more boundaries. Agnes Varda is the essence of art.

Oh my god! There’s a reason Scorsese calls this “the best debut film ever made.” Truffaut put a fork in the road and redirected the course of cinema. We owe so much to him. My heart goes out to Antoine and teenage François, though he managed to turn a f*cked up childhood into indelible art.
